SIMPLE: hunch
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hunch
<hw>Hunch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. akin to
<ets>huckle</ets>; cf. <ets>hump</ets>, <ets>hunch</ets>,
<ets>bunch</ets>, <ets>hunk</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A hump; a
protuberance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A lump; a thick piece; <as>as, a <ex>hunch</ex> of
bread</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A push or thrust, as with the elbow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A strong, intuitive impression that something will
happen; -- said to be from the gambler's superstition that it brings
luck to touch the hump of a hunchback.</def> <mark>[Colloq. or
Slang]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Get a <xex>hunch</xex>, bet a bunch.⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> presentiment, premonition.</syn>
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hunch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hunch
<hw>Hunch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hunched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hunching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To push or jostle
with the elbow; to push or thrust suddenly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To thrust out a hump or protuberance; to crook, as
the back.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hunchback</ent>⟦br⟧
